  	    "thumbnailUrl": "http://media.gq.com/photos/55828d59e52bc4b477a984c6/master/pass/blogs-the-feed-jerry-sandusky-happy-valley-documentary.jpg",
  	    "datePublished": "2014-11-21T06:00:00.000Z",
  	    "dateModified": "2015-06-18T09:20:25.618Z",
  	    "articleSection": "News &amp; Culture",
  	    "description": "Photo: Patrick Smith/Getty Images The creepiest found footage you\u0027re likely to see in a movie anytime soon shows a cheerful man romping with a bunch of screamingly excited children. That\u0027s because the man is...",
  	    "articleBody": "FacebookPinterest\u000A\u000A Photo: Patrick Smith/Getty Images\u000A\u000AThe creepiest found footage you\u0027re likely to see in a movie anytime soon shows a cheerful man romping with a bunch of screamingly excited children. That\u0027s because the man is Jerry Sandusky, the kids are lucky attendees at his charity camp for underprivileged tykes, and the movie is Happy Valley, Amir Bar-Lev\u0027s fine-toned documentary about the grisly child-predator scandal that A) sent Sandusky to prison for life, which doesn\u0027t seem nearly long enough, B) put legendary Penn State coach Joe Paterno out of job with his reputation in tatters after nearly half a century of Sports Illustrated godhood, and C) shattered the school\u0027s beloved status as college football\u0027s Jedi knights for, undoubtedly, years to come.\u000A\u000AWhich of those outcomes defines your concern with the case is one of the great American Rorschasch blots. Bar-Lev—a filmmaker uncommonly attentive to how people\u0027s perspectives express their values, as 2010\u0027s The Tillman Story showed—does a terrific job of conveying that. Penn Staters won\u0027t be happy with the movie, but it\u0027s fundamentally compassionate and never badgering.\u000A\u000ANot, of course, that the director has any interest in mitigating Sandusky\u0027s creepiness. As you already know if you remember the perp\u0027s clueless 2011 interview with Bob Costas on NBC\u0027s Rock Center, which isn\u0027t included here, part of what makes him so revealing as a monster is that he\u0027s such a clod. It\u0027s almost as if being exposed as a pedophile was the first evidence he had any inner life at all, making ye olde banality of evil resonate to beat the Penn State marching band. But his m.o. wasn\u0027t what you\u0027d call improvisational, since he seems to have founded Second Mile essentially to give himself creditable-looking access to a steady supply of juvenile victims. Once an organization man, always an organization man.\u000A\u000AIn the only scene in Happy Valley that shows him interacting with anyone after the scandal broke—he\u0027s fending off a reporter who\u0027s shown up on his doorstep—his complacent affability is more disconcerting than exasperation or twitchy panic would have been. Acting like genial, ever-obliging Jerry Sandusky, now as loyally subordinate to his lawyer as he ever was to Paterno, is the only public role he knows. He isn\u0027t about to let a minor glitch like being an accused serial child rapist reboot that familiar routine.\u000A\u000AHowever, Sandusky himself isn\u0027t Bar-Lev\u0027s only or even major focus of interest. Damn near mercifully, because the less time spent in his company the better, he grows less central as the scandal\u0027s ripple effects take hold, tainting Paterno\u0027s reputation, compromising Penn State\u0027s trustworthiness as an institution, and catapulting pretty much everyone with an emotional stake in \u0022Joe Pa,\u0022 the school and/or its football team into various states of denial, pigheaded defiance, and misdirected anger.\u000A\u000ANobody comes off especially well except for Matt Sandusky, Jerry\u0027s adopted son, who clinched the case against the predator when he bravely came forward midway through the trial with his own history of abuse. To a lesser extent, Scott Paterno, the less blinkered two of Joe\u0027s boys, also shows some welcome decency. Yet to Bar-Lev\u0027s credit, he isn\u0027t out to simple-mindedly condemn Penn State, the fans, or the whole culture of worship surrounding Paterno and the Nittany Lions that ended up as Sandusky\u0027s enabler. He just wants to understand it all, which is not only more humane but ultimately more, well, useful.\u000A\u000AHappy Valley wouldn\u0027t be anywhere near as haunting if it didn\u0027t catch the lyrical side of doting on a football team—the beauty of game-day rituals, the communal identification with countless strangers, the alleviation of the rest of life\u0027s bewilderments—along with adulation\u0027s limits as a moral guide to all the stuff we count on football for reprieves from. However foolish they may be, there\u0027s nothing ignoble about those desires. Even the cult of Joe Pa, which was and is kind of perturbing, would have been more likely to earn a \u0022yeesh\u0022 instead of a \u0022yikes\u0022 from outsiders if Sandusky\u0027s free ride hadn\u0027t suddenly left it looking pernicious. What Bar-Lev doesn\u0027t lose sight of is that, if the culture he depicts ended up abetting Sandusky\u0027s crimes—and it did—that was partly because it wasn\u0027t any more designed to deal with them than a musical comedy is to guard against velociraptor attacks.\u000A\u000AFrom Paterno to the undergrads who rioted (with spectacularly misplaced chants of \u0022Fuck the media!\u0022) when he was fired, naivete is the constant here. In however grotesque a way, even Sandusky had it. The students\u0027 hysteria is often appalling—anyone who tries to wrestle them back into remembering Sandusky\u0027s victims is resented—but it\u0027s also poignant. Few of us react well to having our identities shredded, maybe especially when those identifies are invested in something as frivolous but, at least most of the time, morally anodyne as sports.\u000A\u000AWell aware that he\u0027s depicting a crisis of religious faith, Bar-Lev dwells to beautiful effect on the fate of the relics of Paterno\u0027s not-quite-secular sainthood—the statue the administration finally took down when the NCAA voided his record from 1998 on, the campus mural that gave him pride of place and that the artist kept altering once the scandal broke. First he paints over Sandusky, then he adds a halo above Paterno\u0027s head when Joe Pa dies of cancer just three months after getting fired. Then he scrubs the halo too before figuring out a reconciliatory compromise.\u000A\u000AThe forlorn final version of the muralist\u0027s tribute is a heartbreaker, somehow perfect even in its inadequacy. If you\u0027re tempted to scoff, you won\u0027t be once you ask yourself just what an adequate expression of the flock\u0027s regret would look like.",
  	    "author": ["Tom Carson"],
